Yes.

273
00:33:59,519 --> 00:34:07,930
If we say a system has high quality or low complexity.

274
00:34:07,930 --> 00:34:13,489
What do we really mean?

275
00:34:13,489 --> 00:34:17,489
Quality can include reliability, usability.

276
00:34:17,489 --> 00:34:25,739
Performance, maintainability, and many other attributes.

277
00:34:25,739 --> 00:34:38,380
Complexity can depend on structure, dependencies, control flow, and even human understanding.

278
00:34:38,380 --> 00:34:47,380
Efforts may involve the time, cost, experience level, and team coordination.

279
00:34:47,380 --> 00:34:58,269
So, reducing all of this into one number can destroy important information.

280
00:34:58,269 --> 00:35:08,269
The key idea here is moving from naive ranking to regions.

281
00:35:08,269 --> 00:35:11,269
Multi-dimensional measurements.

282
00:35:11,269 --> 00:35:21,929
Naive ranking means we simply order systems from best to worst.

283
00:35:21,929 --> 00:35:23,929
Based on one value.

284
00:35:23,929 --> 00:35:32,340
But real measurements should preserve relationships between entities.

285
00:35:32,340 --> 00:35:37,340
Measurement is not just assigning numbers.

286
00:35:37,340 --> 00:35:42,820
It's about representing reality in a structured way.

287
00:35:42,820 --> 00:35:47,820
If two systems are different in different dimensions.

288
00:35:47,820 --> 00:35:52,820
For example, one is faster but more expensive.

289
00:35:52,820 --> 00:35:59,820
How can a single number truly represent that trade-off?

290
00:35:59,820 --> 00:36:05,699
In many cases, it's not.

291
00:36:05,699 --> 00:36:07,769
It cannot.

292
00:36:07,769 --> 00:36:21,769
That's why multi-dimensional measurements using vectors or multiple attributes is often more accurate and more honest.

