597
00:58:13,159 --> 00:58:21,900
So far, we discussed the direct measurement and vector representation.

598
00:58:21,900 --> 00:58:28,900
But in practice, we often combine measures to create a new one.

599
00:58:28,900 --> 00:58:32,639
This is called a derivative measure.

600
00:58:32,639 --> 00:58:35,639
A classic example is density.

601
00:58:35,639 --> 00:58:38,639
We define density as

602
00:58:38,639 --> 00:58:45,630
density d is equal to mass over volume, m over v.

603
00:58:45,630 --> 00:58:50,630
Here, mass and volume are direct measures.

604
00:58:50,630 --> 00:58:53,630
Density is derived from them.

605
00:58:53,630 --> 00:58:56,630
But there is an important condition.

606
00:58:56,630 --> 00:59:02,630
The relationship must remain valid under rescaling.

607
00:59:02,630 --> 00:59:07,579
What does rescaling mean?

608
00:59:07,579 --> 00:59:11,960
It means changing the units.

609
00:59:11,960 --> 00:59:17,860
For example, we can measure mass in grams or kilograms.

610
00:59:17,860 --> 00:59:22,860
We can measure volume in liters or cubic meters.

611
00:59:22,860 --> 00:59:25,860
These are different units.

612
00:59:25,860 --> 00:59:29,860
But they represent the same physical reality.

613
00:59:29,860 --> 00:59:38,119
A valid derivative measure must behave consistently when units change.

614
00:59:38,119 --> 00:59:41,119
If we multiply mass by a constant factor,

615
00:59:41,119 --> 00:59:44,119
because we change units,

616
00:59:44,119 --> 00:59:51,119
the density value should transform in a predictable and admissible way.

617
00:59:51,119 --> 00:59:55,659
It should not suddenly destroy the relationship.

618
00:59:55,659 --> 01:00:00,079
So, the rule is this.

619
01:00:00,079 --> 01:00:10,079
A derivative measure is meaningful only if admissible transformations of the components lead to admissible transformations.

620
01:00:10,079 --> 01:00:21,719
If mass is rescaled properly and volume is rescaled properly,

621
01:00:21,719 --> 01:00:25,719
then density must also rescale correctly.

622
01:00:25,719 --> 01:00:29,039
If that does not happen,

623
01:00:29,039 --> 01:00:36,929
the derived formula is not meaningful from a measurement theory perspective.

624
01:00:36,929 --> 01:00:40,929
Now think about software engineering.

625
01:00:40,929 --> 01:00:49,090
When we define metrics like productivity equals to line of code over effort.

626
01:00:49,090 --> 01:00:54,090
The productivity is equal lines of code over effort.

627
01:00:54,090 --> 01:01:00,119
Or defect density equals to defects over kilo.

628
01:01:00,119 --> 01:01:05,119
We are also creating derived measures.

629
01:01:05,119 --> 01:01:07,119
We must check,

630
01:01:07,119 --> 01:01:09,119
we must control

631
01:01:09,119 --> 01:01:11,119
whether changing units,

632
01:01:11,119 --> 01:01:12,119
for example,

633
01:01:12,119 --> 01:01:15,119
from lines to thousands of lines,

634
01:01:15,119 --> 01:01:19,119
produces valid transformations.

635
01:01:19,119 --> 01:01:25,789
If the scale types of the components are weak,

636
01:01:25,789 --> 01:01:31,039
the derivative measure cannot be stronger than them.

637
01:01:31,039 --> 01:01:32,039
For example,

638
01:01:32,039 --> 01:01:37,039
if one component is only ordinal,

639
01:01:37,039 --> 01:01:42,519
the final measure cannot magically

640
01:01:42,519 --> 01:01:45,960
become a gracious scale.

641
01:01:45,960 --> 01:01:50,409
So, the key idea here is discipline.

642
01:01:50,409 --> 01:01:54,989
Combining numbers is easy.

643
01:01:54,989 --> 01:02:01,010
Creating a meaningful derivative measure is much harder.

644
01:02:01,010 --> 01:02:05,900
Whenever we define a new metric,

645
01:02:05,900 --> 01:02:08,000
we should ask,

646
01:02:08,000 --> 01:02:12,030
does it remain valid under rescaling?

647
01:02:12,030 --> 01:02:15,570
Does it preserve the structure of the old one?

648
01:02:15,570 --> 01:02:29,659
The structure of the original attributes?

649
01:02:29,659 --> 01:02:35,750
Yes, the next slide is slide number seven.

